oc:kn_01fc610b a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating @staticmethod or @classmethod decorators" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Map Python static methods and class methods to Scala companion objects (object with same name as class)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Scala has no static keyword; companion objects are the idiomatic way to define class-level methods and factory constructors." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_23ab12c0 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating Python @property setters" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Prefer immutable case classes with require guards over mutable classes with getter/setter patterns. Only use var-based mutable properties when mutability is truly needed." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Immutable data design is idiomatic Scala and reduces side-effect bugs; the mutable Circle pattern with _radius should be a fallback, not the default." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_3c7128b0 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating Python singleton patterns" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Do not try to replicate Python's __new__-based singleton pattern in Scala. Use Scala's 'object' keyword which is a singleton by definition." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Scala objects are JVM-level singletons guaranteed by the language — manual singleton implementations are unnecessary and error-prone." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_6501a64b a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating Python dataclasses or simple value-holding classes" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Prefer Scala case classes over regular classes for data-holding types — they auto-generate equals, hashCode, toString, copy, and apply, mirroring Python dataclasses." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Case classes are the idiomatic Scala way to represent immutable data and eliminate boilerplate." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_7c576ff1 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating Python Enum classes" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use sealed traits with case class/case object subtypes for enum-like hierarchies (Scala 2) or Scala 3 enums for exhaustive pattern matching." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Sealed hierarchies enable the compiler to check exhaustiveness in pattern matching, which has no direct Python equivalent." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_8ade2fc2 a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating Python operator overloading or special methods" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Map Python dunder methods to Scala equivalents: __init__ → primary constructor, __str__/__repr__ → toString, __eq__ → equals, __hash__ → hashCode, __add__ → + method, __getitem__ → apply, __setitem__ → update, __iter__ → extend Iterable trait, __lt__/__le__ → extend Ordered trait." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Scala uses named methods for operator overloading; case classes auto-generate equals/hashCode/toString, so manual implementation is only needed for custom behavior." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_ca5f9adc a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating Python ABCs or multiple inheritance hierarchies" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use Scala traits instead of abstract classes for interfaces, and use trait mixing (with keyword) to replicate Python's multiple inheritance." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Traits are Scala's primary composition mechanism and support mixin composition analogous to Python's multiple inheritance." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_e2744ff8 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing Scala instantiation code" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Regular Scala classes require 'new' keyword for instantiation; case classes do not. Case classes use no-arg apply in companion object." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Mixing up instantiation syntax is a common source of compilation errors for Python developers new to Scala." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

